                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Cum huic Annibalis obiectioni responsum est, omnes deinceps oppositiones solutu faciles. Iamq[ue] Roma[e] vacat, de maximis mundi 
                        decisionibus deliberare. De cupiditate Nini regis, qui, ut latius dominaretur, primus intulit bella finitimis. Augustinus L. 4. c. 6. 
                        de ciuit. dej. A principio ad finem Liuiana[e] historia[e], prima, ultimaq[ue] hypothesis, S. P. Q. Romani. Sapere, capere, rapere, 
                        tria Romana Principia. Molientibus non proficere, deficere est: et grassantibus non progredi, est regredi.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Hannibal"/>
                    <person name="Ninus"/>
                    <person name="Augustine"/>
                    <person name="Livy"/>
                    <book title="Ab Urbe Condita"/>
                    <book title="De Civitate Dei"/>
                    <location name="Rome"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                When this opposition of Hannibal was addressed, all hostile moves thereafter were easy to solve. And at this point Rome had the opportunity to
                consider the most important settlements in the world. Of the greed of King Ninus, who was the first to make war on his neighbours in order to 
                rule more widely: Augustine’s City of God bk. 4, ch. 6. From the beginning to the end of Livy’s history the Senate and the People of Rome is 
                the first and final case. To be wise, to seize, to sack: the three Roman principles. For those who strive, making no progress amounts to 
                failing; and for those who press on making no advance amounts to retreating.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
